<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra" title=3D"Lin=
ear algebra">linear algebra</a>, the <b>singular value decomposition</b> (<=
b>SVD</b>) is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_decompositi=
on" title=3D"Matrix decomposition">factorization</a> of a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real</a> or <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex numbe=
r">complex</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics=
)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">matrix</a> into a rotation, followed by a=
 rescaling followed by another rotation. It generalizes the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigendecomposition" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Eigendecomposition">eigendecomposition</a> of a square <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_matrix" title=3D"Normal matrix">normal matr=
ix</a> with an orthonormal eigenbasis to any <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=
