<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Signal_processing">Signal p=
rocessing</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSi=
ngular_value_decomposition&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edi=
t section: Signal processing"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The SVD and pseudoinverse have been successfully applied to <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal_processing" title=3D"Signal processing"=
>signal processing</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-8"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_processing" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Image processing">image processing</a><sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-Mademlis2018_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-Mademlis2018-9"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" title=3D"Big da=
ta">big data</a> (e.g., in genomic signal processing).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singular_va=
lue_decomposition#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singular_value_decompos=
ition#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_=
note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-13"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_examples">Other examp=
les</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSingular=
_value_decomposition&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Other examples"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The SVD is also applied extensively to the study of linear <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_problem" title=3D"Inverse problem">inve=
rse problems</a> and is useful in the analysis of regularization methods su=
ch as that of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tikhonov_regularizat=
ion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tikhonov regularization">Tikhonov</a>. =
It is widely used in statistics, where it is related to <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis" title=3D"Principal comp=
onent analysis">principal component analysis</a> and to <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correspondence_analysis" title=3D"Correspondence anal=
ysis">correspondence analysis</a>, and in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Signal_processing" title=3D"Signal processing">signal processing</a=
> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pattern_recognition" title=
=3D"Pattern recognition">pattern recognition</a>. It is also used in output=
-only <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_analysis" title=3D"Mod=
al analysis">modal analysis</a>, where the non-scaled <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode_shape" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mode shape">=
mode shapes</a> can be determined from the singular vectors. Yet another us=
age is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latent_semantic_indexing" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Latent semantic indexing">latent semantic ind=
exing</a> in natural-language text processing.
</p><p>In general numerical computation involving linear or linearized syst=
ems, there is a universal constant that characterizes the regularity or sin=
gularity of a problem, which is the system's "condition number" <span class=
=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathm=
l-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http=
://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \kappa :=3D\sigma=
 _{\text{max}}/\sigma _{\text{min}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>=CE=BA<!-- =CE=BA --></mi>
        <mo>:=3D</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mtext>max</mtext>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mtext>min</mtext>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \kappa :=3D\s=
igma _{\text{max}}/\sigma _{\text{min}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/22c7ceb11dc2c4b423f3b697034b1e64beb13d0b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:15.165ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \k=
appa :=3D\sigma _{\text{max}}/\sigma _{\text{min}}}"></span>. It often cont=
rols the error rate or convergence rate of a given computational scheme on =
such systems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-14"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The SVD also plays a crucial role in the field of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_information" title=3D"Quantum information">q=
uantum information</a>, in a form often referred to as the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schmidt_decomposition" title=3D"Schmidt decomposit=
ion">Schmidt decomposition</a>. Through it, states of two quantum systems a=
re naturally decomposed, providing a necessary and sufficient condition for=
 them to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_entanglement" =
title=3D"Quantum entanglement">entangled</a>: if the rank of the <span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-math=
ml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"htt=
p://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \mathbf {\Sigma =
} }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">=CE=A3<!-- =CE=A3 --></mi>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathbf {\Sig=
ma } }</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/90f99b56fe6ada781ecd0f8a45b6e787b6dfed56" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.931ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ma=
thbf {\Sigma } }"></span> matrix is larger than one.
</p><p>One application of SVD to rather large matrices is in <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_weather_prediction" title=3D"Numerical=
 weather prediction">numerical weather prediction</a>, where <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lanczos_algorithm" title=3D"Lanczos algorithm">L=
anczos methods</a> are used to estimate the most linearly quickly growing f=
ew perturbations to the central numerical weather prediction over a given i=
nitial forward time period; i.e., the singular vectors corresponding to the=
 largest singular values of the linearized propagator for the global weathe=
r over that time interval. The output singular vectors in this case are ent=
ire weather systems. These perturbations are then run through the full nonl=
inear model to generate an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ensembl=
e_forecasting" title=3D"Ensemble forecasting">ensemble forecast</a>, giving=
 a handle on some of the uncertainty that should be allowed for around the =
current central prediction.
</p><p>SVD has also been applied to reduced order modelling. The aim of red=
uced order modelling is to reduce the number of degrees of freedom in a com=
plex system which is to be modeled. SVD was coupled with <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radial_basis_functions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Radial basis functions">radial basis functions</a> to interpolate solut=
ions to three-dimensional unsteady flow problems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singular_value_d=
ecomposition#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Interestingly, SVD has been used to improve gravitational waveform m=
odeling by the ground-based gravitational-wave interferometer aLIGO.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> SVD can help to i=
ncrease the accuracy and speed of waveform generation to support gravitatio=
nal-waves searches and update two different waveform models.
</p><p>Singular value decomposition is used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Recommender_systems" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Recommende=
r systems">recommender systems</a> to predict people's item ratings.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Distributed algor=
ithms have been developed for the purpose of calculating the SVD on cluster=
s of commodity machines.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-19=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p><p>Low-rank SVD has been applied for hotspot detection from spatiotempo=
ral data with application to disease <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Outbreak" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Outbreak">outbreak</a> detectio=
n.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A combin=
ation of SVD and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Higher-order_sing=
ular_value_decomposition" title=3D"Higher-order singular value decompositio=
n">higher-order SVD</a> also has been applied for real time event detection=
 from complex data streams (multivariate data with space and time dimension=
s) in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disease_surveillance" title=
=3D"Disease surveillance">disease surveillance</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singular_value=
_decomposition#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astrodynamics" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Astrodynamics">astrodynamics</a>, the SVD and its var=
iants are used as an option to determine suitable maneuver directions for t=
