ralidharan2021_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-Muralidharan2021-23"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>The SVD can be used to measure the similarity between real-valued ma=
trices.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-albers2025_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-albers=
2025-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> By measuring the angles between the singular vectors, =
the inherent two-dimensional structure of matrices is accounted for. This m=
ethod was shown to outperform <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosi=
ne_similarity" title=3D"Cosine similarity">cosine similarity</a> and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frobenius_norm" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Frobenius norm">Frobenius norm</a> in most cases, including brain ac=
tivity measurements from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroscie=
nce" title=3D"Neuroscience">neuroscience</a> experiments.
</p>
