<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSingular_value_decompo=
sition&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D43" title=3D"Edit section: History">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<p>The singular value decomposition was originally developed by <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_geometry" title=3D"Differential =
geometry">differential geometers</a>, who wished to determine whether a rea=
l <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilinear_form" title=3D"Bilinear=
 form">bilinear form</a> could be made equal to another by independent orth=
ogonal transformations of the two spaces it acts on. <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugenio_Beltrami" title=3D"Eugenio Beltrami">Eugenio Bel=
trami</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camille_Jordan" titl=
e=3D"Camille Jordan">Camille Jordan</a> discovered independently, in 1873 a=
nd 1874 respectively, that the singular values of the bilinear forms, repre=
sented as a matrix, form a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complet=
e_set_of_invariants" title=3D"Complete set of invariants">complete set</a> =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invariant_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Invariant (mathematics)">invariants</a> for bilinear forms under orthog=
onal substitutions. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Joseph_S=
ylvester" title=3D"James Joseph Sylvester">James Joseph Sylvester</a> also =
arrived at the singular value decomposition for real square matrices in 188=
9, apparently independently of both Beltrami and Jordan. Sylvester called t=
he singular values the <i>canonical multipliers</i> of the matrix <span cla=
ss=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inl=
ine"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"d=
isplay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=
=3D"{\displaystyle \mathbf {A} .}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">A</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathbf {A} .=
}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/ae3d0814d4c81a814b240ffd86eff80b36945131" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:2.666ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ma=
thbf {A} .}"></span>=E2=81=A0</span> The fourth mathematician to discover t=
he singular value decomposition independently is <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/L%C3%A9on_Autonne" title=3D"L=C3=A9on Autonne">Autonne</a> i=
n 1915, who arrived at it via the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Polar_decomposition" title=3D"Polar decomposition">polar decomposition</a>.=
 The first proof of the singular value decomposition for rectangular and co=
mplex matrices seems to be by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl=
_Eckart" title=3D"Carl Eckart">Carl Eckart</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Gale_J._Young" title=3D"Gale J. Young">Gale J. Young</a> i=
n 1936;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the=
y saw it as a generalization of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Principal_axis_theorem" title=3D"Principal axis theorem">principal axis</=
a> transformation for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermitian_ma=
trix" title=3D"Hermitian matrix">Hermitian matrices</a>.
</p><p>In 1907, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erhard_Schmidt" ti=
tle=3D"Erhard Schmidt">Erhard Schmidt</a> defined an analog of singular val=
ues for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral_operator" title=
=3D"Integral operator">integral operators</a> (which are compact, under som=
e weak technical assumptions); it seems he was unaware of the parallel work=
 on singular values of finite matrices. This theory was further developed b=
y <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89mile_Picard" title=3D"=C3=
=89mile Picard">=C3=89mile Picard</a> in 1910, who is the first to call the=
 numbers <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span cla=
ss=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"=
><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaysty=
le \sigma _{k}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \sigma _{k}}<=
/annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/330415aef0a06818b843c55814fda645b793811b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:2.416ex; height:2.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \si=
gma _{k}}"></span> <i>singular values</i> (or in French, <i>valeurs singuli=
=C3=A8res</i>).
</p><p>Practical methods for computing the SVD date back to <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ervand_Kogbetliantz" title=3D"Ervand Kogbetliantz=
">Kogbetliantz</a> in 1954=E2=80=931955 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Magnus_Hestenes" title=3D"Magnus Hestenes">Hestenes</a> in 1958,<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> resembling =
closely the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacobi_eigenvalue_algo=
rithm" title=3D"Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm">Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm</a=
>, which uses plane rotations or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
ivens_rotation" title=3D"Givens rotation">Givens rotations</a>. However, th=
ese were replaced by the method of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Gene_H._Golub" title=3D"Gene H. Golub">Gene Golub</a> and <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Kahan" title=3D"William Kahan">William Kah=
an</a> published in 1965,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGolubKahan1965_28-1" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singular_value_=
decomposition#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGolubKahan1965-28"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which uses <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Householder_transformation" title=
=3D"Householder transformation">Householder transformations</a> or reflecti=
ons. In 1970, Golub and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_=
Reinsch" title=3D"Christian Reinsch">Christian Reinsch</a> published a vari=
ant of the Golub/Kahan algorithm<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGolubReinsch197=
0_41-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singul=
ar_value_decomposition#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGolubReinsch1970-41"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 that is still the one most-used today.
</p>
